Frozen Foods is in compliance with the OSHA PSM requirements and has conducted a process hazard analysis on the ammonia refrigeration system.

There is only one RMP-covered ammonia process at Pioneer Frozen Foods - the Main System which holds a maximum of 39,700 pounds of anhydrous ammonia.  The second process, Aero-Freezer #1 System is actually below the threshold since it only contains a maximum of 3,500 pounds.  The third system, Aero-Freezer #2 System, is also below the PSM and RMP thresholds since it holds a maximum of 4,000 pounds.  These latter two systems are separate from each other and from the Main system.
    The worst case and alternative release scenarios have been updated using EPA's guidance document, Appendix E: Supplemental Risk Management Program Guidance for Ammonia Refrigeration Facilities (May 2004), which replaced the guidance that was used for the original offsite consequence analysis, the Model Risk Management Program and Plan for Ammonia Refrigeration by SAIC (May 1996).  A copy of Appendix E is included as Appendix E to this document. 
Pioneer Frozen Foods has implemented safety precautions and procedures designed to prevent and mitigate catastrophic releases.  Pioneer Frozen Foods maintains current operating, maintenance, training, and inspection procedures; a trained medical emergency response team; and an evacuation plan for each area.  In addition, the local fire department has inspected the facility.

    Several developments and findings have resulted from the implementation of the various elements of our accidental release prevention program. The upgrade to the alarm system allows the siren to be heard throughout the facility instead of just in designated areas. 

